      "source": [
        "An iterator is an object that represents a stream of data, as mentioned earlier, that is stateful, meant for one-time use.\n",
        "\n",
        "- `__iter__()` method (returns itself)\n",
        "- `__next__()` method (returns the next item, or raises StopIteration when done)"
      ],
      "id": "3a62a10f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "my_list = [1, 2, 3]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Iterable: can be iterated multiple times\n",
        "for x in my_list:\n",
        "    print(x)  # 1, 2, 3\n",
        "\n",
        "for x in my_list:\n",
        "    print(x)  # 1, 2, 3 again!\n",
        "\n",
        "# Iterator: can only be iterated once\n",
        "my_iter = iter(my_list)\n",
        "\n",
        "for x in my_iter:\n",
        "    print(x)  # 1, 2, 3\n",
        "\n",
        "for x in my_iter:\n",
        "    print(x)  # Nothing! Iterator is exhausted"
      ],
      "id": "18ea6dcf",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "`for` loops call `iter()` on an iterable to get an iterator, then repeatedly call `next()` on the iterator.\n"
